# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scim-provisioning-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] In computing, a **directory service** or **name service** maps the names of network resources to their respective network addresses.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] It is a shared information infrastructure for locating, managing, administering and organizing everyday items and network resources, which can include volumes, folders, files, printers, users, groups, devices, telephone numbers and other objects.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] A directory service is a critical component of a network operating system.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] A **directory server** or name server is a server which provides such a service.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Each resource on the network is considered an object by the directory server.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Information about a particular resource is stored as a collection of attributes associated with that resource or object.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] A directory service defines a namespace for the network.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] The namespace is used to assign a *name* (unique identifier) to each of the objects.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Directories typically have a set of rules determining how network resources are named and identified, which usually includes a requirement that the identifiers be unique and unambiguous.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] When using a directory service, a user does not have to remember the physical address of a network resource; providing a name locates the resource.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Some directory services include access control provisions, limiting the availability of directory information to authorized users.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Several things distinguish a directory service from a relational database.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Attributes are sometimes multi-valued, allowing multiple naming attributes at one level (such as machine type and serial number concatenation, or multiple phone numbers for "work phone").
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Attributes and object classes are usually standardized throughout the industry; for example, X.500 attributes and classes are often formally registered with the IANA for their object ID.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Therefore, directory applications try to reuse standard classes and attributes to maximize the benefit of existing directory-server software.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Object instances are slotted into namespaces; each object class inherits from its parent object class (and ultimately from the root of the hierarchy), adding attributes to the must-may list.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Directory services are often central to the security design of an IT system and have a correspondingly-fine granularity of access control.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Replication and distribution have distinct meanings in the design and management of a directory service.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Replication is used to indicate that the same directory namespace (the same objects) are copied to another directory server for redundancy and throughput reasons; the replicated namespace is governed by the same authority.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Distribution is used to indicate that multiple directory servers in different namespaces are interconnected to form a distributed directory service; each namespace can be governed by a different authority.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Directory services were part of an Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) initiative for common network standards and multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] During the 1980s, the ITU and ISO created the X.500 set of standards for directory services, initially to support the requirements of inter-carrier electronic messaging and network-name lookup.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is based on the X.500 directory-information services, using the TCP/IP stack and an X.500 Directory Access Protocol (DAP) string-encoding scheme on the Internet.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Open-source tools to create directory services include OpenLDAP, the Kerberos protocol and Samba software, which can function as a Windows domain controller with Kerberos and LDAP back ends.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Administration is by GOsa or Samba SWAT.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Name services on Unix systems are typically configured through nsswitch.conf.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/directory-service] Information from name services can be retrieved with getent.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Despite its name, LDAP is much more than its protocol (i.e., much more than its HTTP API); it includes specifications of the required operation of systems satisfying its HTTP API and even specifies a standardized model of the data to be used by the HTTP API and managed by the directory service.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory services play an important role in developing intranet and Internet applications by allowing the sharing of information about users, systems, networks, services, and applications throughout the network.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As examples, directory services may provide any organized set of records, often with a hierarchical structure, such as a corporate email directory.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, a telephone directory is a list of subscribers with an address and a phone number.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common use of LDAP is to provide a central place to store usernames and passwords.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This allows many different applications and services to connect to the LDAP server to validate users.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is a simpler (*lightweight*) subset of the standards in the X.500 series, particularly the X.511 Directory Access Protocol.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Because of this relationship, LDAP is sometimes called **X.500 Lite**.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Telecommunication companies' understanding of directory requirements were well developed after some 70 years of producing and managing telephone directories.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These companies introduced the concept of directory services to information technology and computer networking, their input culminating in the comprehensive X.500 specification, a suite of protocols produced by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) in the 1980s.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] X.500 directory services were traditionally accessed via the X.511 Directory Access Protocol (DAP), which required the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) protocol stack.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP was originally intended to be a lightweight alternative protocol for accessing X.500 directory services through the simpler (and now widespread) TCP/IP protocol stack.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This model of directory access was borrowed from the DIXIE and Directory Assistance Service protocols.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The protocol was originally created by Tim Howes of the University of Michigan, Steve Kille of Isode Limited, Colin Robbins of Nexor and Wengyik Yeong of Performance Systems International, circa 1993, as a successor to DIXIE and DAS.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Mark Wahl of Critical Angle Inc., Tim Howes, and Steve Kille started work in 1996 on a new version of LDAP, LDAPv3, under the aegis of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPv3, first published in 1997, superseded LDAPv2 and added support for extensibility, integrated the Simple Authentication and Security Layer, and better aligned the protocol to the 1993 edition of X.500.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Further development of the LDAPv3 specifications themselves and of numerous extensions adding features to LDAPv3 has come through the IETF.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the early engineering stages of LDAP, it was known as *Lightweight Directory Browsing Protocol*, or *LDBP*.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was renamed with the expansion of the scope of the protocol beyond directory browsing and searching, to include directory update functions.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was given its *Lightweight* name because it was not as network intensive as its DAP predecessor and thus was more easily implemented over the Internet due to its relatively modest bandwidth usage.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP has influenced subsequent Internet protocols, including later versions of X.500, XML Enabled Directory (XED), Directory Service Markup Language (DSML), Service Provisioning Markup Language (SPML), and the Service Location Protocol (SLP).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It is also used as the basis for Microsoft's Active Directory.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A client starts an LDAP session by connecting to an LDAP server, called a Directory System Agent (DSA), by default on TCP and UDP port 389, or on port 636 for LDAPS (LDAP over TLS/SSL, see below).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client then sends an operation request to the server, and a server sends responses in return.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] With some exceptions, the client does not need to wait for a response before sending the next request, and the server may send the responses in any order.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] All information is transmitted using Basic Encoding Rules (BER).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In addition the server may send "Unsolicited Notifications" that are not responses to any request, e.g. before the connection is timed out.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common alternative method of securing LDAP communication is using an SSL tunnel.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The default port for LDAP over SSL is 636.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The use of LDAP over SSL was common in LDAP Version 2 (LDAPv2) but it was never standardized in any formal specification.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This usage has been deprecated along with LDAPv2, which was officially retired in 2003.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A DN may change over the lifetime of the entry, for instance, when entries are moved within a tree.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To reliably and unambiguously identify entries, a UUID might be provided in the set of the entry's *operational attributes*.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`dn`" is the distinguished name of the entry; it is neither an attribute nor a part of the entry.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`cn=John Doe`" is the entry's RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), and "`dc=example,dc=com`" is the DN of the parent entry, where "`dc`" denotes 'Domain Component'.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The other lines show the attributes in the entry.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attribute names are typically mnemonic strings, like "`cn`" for common name, "`dc`" for domain component, "`mail`" for email address, and "`sn`" for surname.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A server holds a subtree starting from a specific entry, e.g.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may also hold references to other servers, so an attempt to access "`ou=department,dc=example,dc=com`" could return a *referral* or *continuation reference* to a server that holds that part of the directory tree.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client can then contact the other server.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some servers also support *chaining*, which means the server contacts the other server and returns the results to the client.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP rarely defines any ordering: The server may return the values of an attribute, the attributes in an entry, and the entries found by a search operation in any order.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This follows from the formal definitions - an entry is defined as a set of attributes, and an attribute is a set of values, and sets need not be ordered.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The ADD operation inserts a new entry into the directory-server database.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the distinguished name in the add request already exists in the directory, then the server will not add a duplicate entry but will set the result code in the add result to decimal 68, "entryAlreadyExists".
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the above example, `uid=user,ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must not exist, and `ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must exist.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When an LDAP session is created, that is, when an LDAP client connects to the server, the **authentication state** of the session is set to anonymous.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The BIND operation establishes the authentication state for a session.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Simple BIND and SASL PLAIN can send the user's DN and password in plaintext, so the connections utilizing either Simple or SASL PLAIN should be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server typically checks the password against the `userPassword` attribute in the named entry.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Anonymous BIND (with empty DN and password) resets the connection to anonymous state.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] SASL (Simple Authentication and Security Layer) BIND provides authentication services through a wide range of mechanisms, e.g.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Kerberos or the client certificate sent with TLS.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND also sets the LDAP protocol version by sending a version number as an integer.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the client requests a version that the server does not support, the server must set the result code in the BIND response to the code for a protocol error.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Normally clients should use LDAPv3, which is the default in the protocol but not always in LDAP libraries.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND had to be the first operation in a session in LDAPv2, but is not required as of LDAPv3.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In LDAPv3, each successful BIND request changes the authentication state of the session and each unsuccessful BIND request resets the authentication state of the session.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an entry, an LDAP client transmits a properly formed delete request to the server.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Search operation is used to both search for and read entries.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name of the base object entry (or possibly the root) relative to which the search is to be performed.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] What elements below the baseObject to search.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] (the entire subtree starting at the base DN).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Criteria to use in selecting elements within scope.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] determine whether the values for those attributes match the filter assertion.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Note that a common misconception is that LDAP data is case-sensitive, whereas in fact matching rules and ordering rules determine matching, comparisons, and relative value relationships.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Which attributes to return in result entries.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Maximum number of entries to return, and maximum time to allow search to run.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These values, however, cannot override any restrictions the server places on size limit and time limit.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Return attribute types only, not attribute values.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server returns the matching entries and potentially continuation references.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The final result will include the result code.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Compare operation takes a DN, an attribute name and an attribute value, and checks if the named entry contains that attribute with that value.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation is used by LDAP clients to request that the LDAP server make changes to existing entries.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attempts to modify entries that do not exist will fail.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] MODIFY requests are subject to access controls as implemented by the server.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation requires that the distinguished name (DN) of the entry be specified, and a sequence of changes.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To replace the value of an existing attribute, use the `replace` keyword.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to update.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an attribute from an entry, use the keyword `delete` and the changetype designator `modify`.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to delete.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is also a Modify-Increment extension which allows an incrementable attribute value to be incremented by a specified amount.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When LDAP servers are in a replicated topology, LDAP clients should consider using the post-read control to verify updates instead of a search after an update.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The post-read control is designed so that applications need not issue a search request after an update – it is bad form to retrieve an entry for the sole purpose of checking that an update worked because of the replication eventual consistency model.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP client should not assume that it connects to the same directory server for each request because architects may have placed load-balancers or LDAP proxies or both between LDAP clients and servers.
