[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] After doing so, the client may then use SASL/EXTERNAL.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] By using the SASL/EXTERNAL, the client requests the server derive its identity from credentials provided at a lower level (such as TLS).
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Though technically the server may use any identity information established at any lower level, typically the server will use the identity information established by TLS.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers also often support the non-standard "LDAPS" ("Secure LDAP", commonly known as "LDAP over SSL") protocol on a separate port, by default 636.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPS differs from LDAP in two ways: 1) upon connect, the client and server establish TLS before any LDAP messages are transferred (without a StartTLS operation) and 2) the LDAPS connection must be closed upon TLS closure.
