[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Abandon operation requests that the server abort an operation named by a message ID.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Neither Abandon nor a successfully abandoned operation send a response.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A similar Cancel extended operation does send responses, but not all implementations support this.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Unbind operation abandons any outstanding operations and closes the connection.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name is of historical origin, and is *not* the opposite of the Bind operation.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients can abort a session by simply closing the connection, but they should use Unbind.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Unbind allows the server to gracefully close the connection and free resources that it would otherwise keep for some time until discovering the client had abandoned the connection.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It also instructs the server to cancel operations that can be canceled, and to not send responses for operations that cannot be canceled.
