[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes are the elements responsible for storing information in a directory, and the schema defines the rules for which attributes may be used in an entry, the kinds of values that those attributes may have, and how clients may interact with those values.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients may learn about the schema elements that the server supports by retrieving an appropriate subschema subentry.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Each entry must have an objectClass attribute, containing named classes defined in the schema.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema definition of the classes of an entry defines what kind of object the entry may represent - e.g. a person, organization or domain.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The object class definitions also define the list of attributes that must contain values and the list of attributes which may contain values.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, an entry representing a person might belong to the classes "top" and "person".
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Membership in the "person" class would require the entry to contain the "sn" and "cn" attributes, and allow the entry also to contain "userPassword", "telephoneNumber", and other attributes.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Since entries may have multiple ObjectClasses values, each entry has a complex of optional and mandatory attribute sets formed from the union of the object classes it represents.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] ObjectClasses can be inherited, and a single entry can have multiple ObjectClasses values that define the available and required attributes of the entry itself.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A parallel to the schema of an objectClass is a class definition and an instance in Object-oriented programming, representing LDAP objectClass and LDAP entry, respectively.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory servers may publish the directory schema controlling an entry at a base DN given by the entry's subschemaSubentry operational attribute.
