[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard was initially called ***Simple Cloud Identity Management*** (and is still called this in some places), but the name was officially changed to *System for Cross-domain Identity Management (SCIM)* when the IETF adopted it.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] Interoperability was demonstrated in October, 2011, at the Cloud Identity Summit, an IAM industry conference.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] There, user accounts were provisioned and de-provisioned across separate systems using SCIM standards, by a collection of IdM software vendors: Okta, CyberArk, Ping Identity, SailPoint, Technology Nexus and UnboundID.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] In March 2012, at IETF 83 in Paris, interoperability tests continued by the same vendors, joined by Salesforce.com, BCPSoft, WSO2, Gluu, and Courion (now SecureAuth) nine companies in total.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SCIM is the second standard for exchanging user data, but it builds on prior standards (e.g.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] SPML, PortableContacts, vCards, and LDAP directory services) in an attempt to be a simpler and more widely adopted solution for cloud services providers.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The SCIM standard is growing in popularity and has been adopted by numerous identity providers as well as applications.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] As adoption of the standard grows, so do the number of tools available.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/system-for-cross-domain-identity-management] The standard leverages a number of open-source libraries to facilitate development and testing frameworks ensure that endpoint's compliance with the SCIM standard.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] People are represented by user objects or login accounts on different systems and applications.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] Note that users need not be able to log into a system or application.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] The user object may be a record in an HR application or an entry in a phone book system, which the user cannot log into but which nonetheless represents the user.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] User objects are generally connected to other parts of a system or application through security entitlements.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] On most systems, this is done by placing a user into one or more security groups, where users of each group are granted some security rights.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] Incidentally, the term lifecycle does not imply that users who have been deactivated will necessarily not be onboarded again.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] For example, employees may leave a company and be re-hired later, or contractors may end their contract only to be hired as employees.
[src:scim-provisioning-deep/user-provisioning-software] A user provisioning system may implement one or more processes to achieve the aforementioned goals.
